    "# §1 — Foundational Thesis and Scope"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1.1 The Formation Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "The question this framework addresses is old and precisely stated: given a collection of atoms whose identities are known, what spatial arrangements do they adopt under specified thermodynamic conditions? This is not a question about trajectories, nor about reaction kinetics, nor about electronic structure per se. It is a question about **endpoints** — the stable or metastable configurations that emerge when interatomic forces drive a system toward equilibrium.\n",
    "\n",
    "We call these endpoints *formations*. A formation is a local minimum on the potential energy surface of a system of $N$ particles interacting through pairwise and multi-body classical potentials at temperature $T$ and density $\\rho$. The engine that produces formations is therefore a mapping:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{F}: \\{Z_1, \\ldots, Z_N\\} \\times (T, \\rho, \\text{seed}) \\;\\longrightarrow\\; \\{\\mathbf{X}^*, \\mathcal{E}^*, \\mathcal{C}\\}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $Z_i$ is the atomic number of particle $i$, $\\mathbf{X}^*$ is the equilibrium geometry, $\\mathcal{E}^*$ is the decomposed energy at that geometry, and $\\mathcal{C}$ is a classification label derived from structural analysis of the result.\n",
    "\n",
    "The mapping is deterministic: the same inputs produce the same output. The seed controls all stochastic elements — initial velocity sampling, perturbation noise, random number generator state — so that every formation is reproducible without ambiguity.\n",
    "\n",
    "This framing has a consequence that should be stated upfront. The engine does not *know* what water looks like. It does not store the fact that water is bent at 104.5° or that the O–H bond length is 0.96 Å. It knows only that oxygen has atomic number 8, mass 15.999 amu, electronegativity 3.44, covalent radius 0.66 Å, and a set of Lennard-Jones parameters derived from the Universal Force Field. If the force field, integration scheme, and thermodynamic boundary conditions are correct, the 104.5° angle and 0.96 Å bond length must *emerge*. If they do not emerge, the methodology has a defect. There is no lookup table to fall back on."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1.2 What This Is Not\n",
    "\n",
    "Clarity about boundaries prevents the kind of scope drift that turns a simulation framework into a collection of special cases.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a quantum chemistry code. No wavefunction is computed, no basis set is expanded, no exchange-correlation functional is evaluated. The potentials used here are analytic closed-form expressions motivated by quantum mechanics — Lennard-Jones captures the Pauli repulsion and London dispersion that arise from electron cloud interactions, Coulomb captures the monopole electrostatic field of net atomic charges — but they are evaluated as classical functions of interatomic distance. Electrons do not appear as explicit degrees of freedom. Where this approximation breaks down (charge transfer, covalent bond formation, orbital hybridization effects), the framework either operates within its valid domain or clearly labels the approximation being made.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a molecular database or a geometry lookup service. No external chemical databases are queried during a formation run. The periodic table provides elemental constants — mass, radius, electronegativity — and nothing else. The fact that methane is tetrahedral, that benzene is planar, that sodium chloride forms a face-centered cubic lattice: these are results the engine must produce, not inputs it consumes.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a general-purpose molecular dynamics package. The engine is optimized for the formation problem: starting from an arbitrary initial configuration, finding what structures the system relaxes into. Long-timescale transport properties (diffusion coefficients, viscosity, thermal conductivity) are outside the primary scope. The trajectories generated here are means to an end — the end being the quenched, classified formation — not objects of study in themselves.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a visualization tool. Rendering, force arrow display, ball-and-stick models, interactive 3D manipulation: these are interface projections that exist for human inspection. Removing every line of visualization code must not change any physical result, any energy value, any formation classification. The physics layer has no dependency on the display layer."
   ]
  },
