    "## 1.3 The Periodic Table Commitment\n",
    "\n",
    "The decision to use the periodic table as the sole fundamental data source is not arbitrary. It establishes a very specific contract about what the engine is allowed to know.\n",
    "\n",
    "For each element $Z \\in [1, 102]$, the following properties are available at startup, compiled into the binary:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Property | Symbol | Units | Physical origin |\n",
    "|----------|--------|-------|----------------|\n",
    "| Atomic number | $Z$ | — | Nuclear charge (defines the element) |\n",
    "| Standard atomic weight | $m$ | amu | Mass-weighted isotopic average |\n",
    "| Covalent radius (single bond) | $r_\\text{cov}^{(1)}$ | Å | Half the internuclear distance in a homonuclear single bond |\n",
    "| Covalent radius (double bond) | $r_\\text{cov}^{(2)}$ | Å | Analogous for double bonds |\n",
    "| Covalent radius (triple bond) | $r_\\text{cov}^{(3)}$ | Å | Analogous for triple bonds |\n",
    "| Van der Waals radius | $r_\\text{vdw}$ | Å | Effective nonbonded contact radius |\n",
    "| Pauling electronegativity | $\\chi$ | — | Tendency to attract electrons in a bond |\n",
    "| First ionization energy | $\\text{IE}_1$ | eV | Energy to remove the outermost electron |\n",
    "| Electron affinity | $\\text{EA}$ | eV | Energy released upon electron attachment |\n",
    "| Valence electrons | $n_v$ | — | Electrons in the outermost shell |\n",
    "\n",
    "Additionally, Lennard-Jones parameters ($\\sigma$, $\\varepsilon$) are stored for 20 elements from the UFF parameterization of Rappé et al. (1992). Elements without explicit parameterization fall back to carbon-like defaults. This fallback is a labeled approximation, not a physical claim.\n",
    "\n",
    "The commitment means the following. If someone hands the engine the formula $\\text{Fe}_2\\text{O}_3$ and says \"what does this form at 300 K?\", the engine must answer using only the properties above plus the laws of classical mechanics. It cannot look up the corundum crystal structure. It cannot import DFT-optimized geometries. It must propagate iron and oxygen atoms under interatomic forces and see what comes out. If corundum comes out, the methodology is working. If something else comes out, either the force field is inadequate for iron oxides (which is a legitimate and documentable limitation) or there is a bug.\n",
    "\n",
    "This constraint also means the engine has a well-defined *domain of validity*. The UFF-based LJ parameterization is accurate for organic molecules, reasonable for simple ionic and metallic systems, and progressively less reliable for lanthanides, actinides, and systems where many-body electronic effects dominate. The framework is honest about this: the self-audit infrastructure (§11) includes failure classification that flags out-of-domain compositions explicitly."
   ]
