    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2.1 The State as the Fundamental Object\n",
    "\n",
    "Every physical operation in this framework — force evaluation, integration, energy computation, structural analysis — reads from and writes to a single data structure: the **State**. The State is the complete instantaneous description of the system. Nothing physical exists outside of it.\n",
    "\n",
    "Formally, a State is the tuple:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathcal{S} = (N, \\; \\mathbf{X}, \\; \\mathbf{V}, \\; \\mathbf{Q}, \\; \\mathbf{M}, \\; \\boldsymbol{\\tau}, \\; \\mathbf{B}, \\; \\mathbf{F}, \\; \\mathcal{E}, \\; \\mathcal{L}, \\; \\mathcal{B})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "These fields partition into three categories based on their mutability during a simulation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Identity (Immutable)\n",
    "\n",
    "| Symbol | Name | Type | Description |\n",
    "|--------|------|------|-------------|\n",
    "| $N$ | Particle count | scalar | Number of atoms. Fixed at construction. |\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{M}$ | Masses | $\\mathbb{R}^N$ | Atomic mass of each particle in amu. Set from periodic table at initialization, never modified. |\n",
    "| $\\boldsymbol{\\tau}$ | Type IDs | $\\mathbb{Z}^N$ | Atomic number $Z$ of each particle. Defines the element. Never modified. |\n",
    "\n",
    "The identity fields answer the question: *what* is the system? They are set once and locked. No integrator, no force model, no analysis tool may change $N$, $\\mathbf{M}$, or $\\boldsymbol{\\tau}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Phase (Dynamic)\n",
    "\n",
    "| Symbol | Name | Type | Description |\n",
    "|--------|------|------|-------------|\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{X}$ | Positions | $\\mathbb{R}^{N \\times 3}$ | Cartesian coordinates in Ångströms. |\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{V}$ | Velocities | $\\mathbb{R}^{N \\times 3}$ | Cartesian velocities in Å/fs. |\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{Q}$ | Charges | $\\mathbb{R}^N$ | Partial atomic charges in elementary charge units $e$. |\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{B}$ | Bond graph | Edge set | Pairs $(i, j)$ representing chemical bonds. Currently static within a simulation. |\n",
    "\n",
    "The phase fields answer the question: *where* is the system and *how fast* is it moving? Positions and velocities evolve under the equations of motion. Charges are typically fixed at initialization (from electronegativity equilibration or assigned values) but are formally dynamic to permit future charge-equilibration schemes. The bond graph is inferred from geometry at initialization and held fixed during dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Scratch (Recomputed)\n",
    "\n",
    "| Symbol | Name | Type | Description |\n",
    "|--------|------|------|-------------|\n",
    "| $\\mathbf{F}$ | Forces | $\\mathbb{R}^{N \\times 3}$ | Total force on each atom in kcal/(mol·Å). |\n",
    "| $\\mathcal{E}$ | Energy ledger | 6 scalars | Decomposed potential energy (bond, angle, torsion, vdW, Coulomb, external). |\n",
    "| $\\mathcal{L}$ | Event log | List | Timestamped annotations (convergence events, topology changes). |\n",
    "| $\\mathcal{B}$ | Periodic box | 3 scalars + flag | Box dimensions $(L_x, L_y, L_z)$ for periodic boundary conditions. |\n",
    "\n",
    "The scratch fields are **not persistent between time steps** in any physically meaningful sense. Forces and energies are fully recomputed from positions at every evaluation. The event log is append-only metadata. The box is typically constant but formally belongs to the boundary conditions rather than the physical state.\n",
    "\n",
    "The distinction matters because it defines what must be saved to reproduce a State (identity + phase) versus what can be regenerated on demand (scratch). A checkpoint file needs $(N, \\mathbf{M}, \\boldsymbol{\\tau}, \\mathbf{X}, \\mathbf{V}, \\mathbf{Q}, \\mathbf{B}, \\mathcal{B})$. Forces and energies are not saved — they are consequences of positions and the force field, and storing them would create opportunities for inconsistency."
   ]
  },
