   "source": [
    "## 2.2 The Energy Ledger\n",
    "\n",
    "The potential energy of the system is not a single number. It is a sum of physically distinct contributions, and the framework requires that every force model report its contribution to the correct term:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U = U_\\text{bond} + U_\\text{angle} + U_\\text{torsion} + U_\\text{vdW} + U_\\text{Coulomb} + U_\\text{external}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is not a bookkeeping convenience. It is a physical requirement. The ability to decompose the total energy into contributions from bond stretching, angle bending, dihedral rotation, van der Waals dispersion, and electrostatic interaction is what allows the engine to diagnose *why* a structure formed the way it did. A formation where $U_\\text{vdW}$ dominates has different physical character than one where $U_\\text{bond}$ dominates, even if the total energies are similar.\n",
    "\n",
    "The ledger is zeroed before every force evaluation. This is not optional. A model that accumulates energies across evaluations would produce drift, and the decomposition would become meaningless.\n",
    "\n",
    "Kinetic energy $K = \\sum_i \\frac{1}{2} m_i |\\mathbf{v}_i|^2$ is not part of the ledger. It is a thermodynamic observable computed from velocities on demand, not a contribution to the potential energy surface. Total energy $E = K + U$ is well-defined only for conservative (NVE) dynamics; in thermostatted (NVT) dynamics, the system exchanges energy with the heat bath and total energy fluctuates by design."
   ]
  },
