    "## 2.3 State Persistence: The File Hierarchy\n",
    "\n",
    "States are serialized through a layered file format hierarchy. The design principle is strict additivity: each format level adds information to the previous level and never modifies or removes it. A parser for level $n$ can read any file at level $n-1$.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{xyzZ} \\;\\subset\\; \\text{xyzA} \\;\\subset\\; \\text{xyzC} \\;\\subset\\; \\text{xyzF}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Level 0: xyzZ — Raw Geometry\n",
    "\n",
    "Standard XYZ format. Atom count, comment line, then element symbol and Cartesian coordinates for each atom. This is the only format the engine *requires* as input. Any molecular visualization tool on earth can read it.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Level 1: xyzA — Annotated\n",
    "\n",
    "Adds structured metadata in YAML-formatted comment headers:\n",
    "- Atom IDs (deterministic: $a_1, a_2, \\ldots$)\n",
    "- Bond table with order and type\n",
    "- Per-atom properties (charge, mass, group membership, flags)\n",
    "\n",
    "Bonds are **inferred** at this stage, not specified by the user. The inference rule is distance-based:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{bonded}(i,j) \\;\\Longleftrightarrow\\; |\\mathbf{r}_i - \\mathbf{r}_j| \\;<\\; f \\cdot \\bigl(r_{\\text{cov},i}^{(k)} + r_{\\text{cov},j}^{(k)}\\bigr)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $f \\approx 1.2$ is a tolerance factor and $k \\in \\{1, 2, 3\\}$ selects the bond order whose covalent radius sum best matches the observed distance. This is an effective approximation — it works well for typical organic and inorganic geometries but can misassign bond orders in strained systems or metallic clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Level 2: xyzC — Constructed\n",
    "\n",
    "Adds construction provenance: a complete ordered record of every operation applied to produce this structure from its source.\n",
    "\n",
    "A construction recipe is a sequence of named steps with parameters:\n",
    "- `supercell(a, b, c)` — replicate the unit cell\n",
    "- `relax(method, steps, dt)` — minimize the structure\n",
    "- `cg(mapping)` — coarse-grain (placeholder)\n",
    "\n",
    "Every recipe carries a SHA-256 hash: $h = \\text{SHA256}(\\text{source geometry} \\,\\|\\, \\text{steps} \\,\\|\\, \\text{parameters})$. If the source changes, the hash changes, and all derived files are invalidated.\n",
    "\n",
    "Reserved slots exist for bulk properties (density, elastic modulus, RDF reference) and coarse-grained properties (bead count, PMF reference). These are initialized to null and populated only by downstream analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Level 3: xyzF — Force Annotated\n",
    "\n",
    "Adds computed force vectors for every atom:\n",
    "- Net force $\\mathbf{F}_i$\n",
    "- **Primary interaction**: the single neighbor exerting the largest force, with full decomposition into LJ and Coulomb components\n",
    "- Statistics: max force, mean force, RMS force\n",
    "- Computation metadata: model, cutoff, parameters, timestamp, hash\n",
    "\n",
    "The primary interaction concept is deliberate. For a 1000-atom system, displaying all $O(N)$ pairwise force contributions per atom produces visual noise. Displaying only the one interaction that dominates each atom's behavior produces physical insight. This is the innovation of the xyzF format: it answers \"what is the strongest thing happening to this atom?\" per atom, not \"what are all the things happening?\""
   ]
