    "## 2.4 Hash Lineage and Provenance\n",
    "\n",
    "Every derived state carries a cryptographic hash that serves as both identity and provenance key.\n",
    "\n",
    "The hash is computed as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "h = \\text{SHA256}\\bigl(\\text{canonical}(\\text{source}) \\;\\|\\; \\text{canonical}(\\text{recipe})\\bigr)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\text{canonical}(\\cdot)$ produces a deterministic byte string from the input (fixed-precision float formatting, sorted keys, normalized whitespace). This ensures that the same physical construction produces the same hash regardless of platform, locale, or timestamp.\n",
    "\n",
    "Hash lineage is append-only. A supercell construction appends a step to the recipe and produces a new hash. A relaxation appends another step and produces another hash. The chain is traceable: given the final hash, one can recover the complete construction history and verify that the current geometry matches the hash.\n",
    "\n",
    "This mechanism serves three functions:\n",
    "1. **Rebuild detection**: if the source `.xyz` changes, all derived `.xyzA`, `.xyzC`, `.xyzF` files are automatically invalidated\n",
    "2. **Regression identity**: the regression detector uses config hashes to establish which parameter set produced which results\n",
    "3. **Provenance auditing**: any formation can be traced back to its exact inputs and construction history"
