    "## 3.1 The Model Interface\n",
    "\n",
    "All interatomic potentials in this framework implement a single contract: given a State, compute forces and energies. The interface is deliberately minimal:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\texttt{eval}: \\mathcal{S} \\times \\Theta \\;\\rightarrow\\; (\\mathbf{F}, \\mathcal{E})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\Theta$ denotes the model parameters (cutoff radius $r_c$, Coulomb constant $k_e$). The model reads the immutable and dynamic fields of $\\mathcal{S}$. It writes *only* the scratch fields $\\mathbf{F}$ and $\\mathcal{E}$. Positions, velocities, identities, and the bond graph are never modified by a force evaluation.\n",
    "\n",
    "This separation of concerns — models compute forces, integrators propagate positions — is not a software pattern. It is a physical requirement. The force on atom $i$ is a function of the current configuration $\\mathbf{X}$ alone (in the Born-Oppenheimer approximation). It does not depend on how the system arrived at that configuration, what temperature was requested, or how many time steps have elapsed.\n",
    "\n",
    "Two model families are implemented:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Nonbonded** (Lennard-Jones + Coulomb): pairwise interactions between all atom pairs, modulated by cutoff and switching\n",
    "2. **Bonded** (molecular mechanics): intramolecular interactions defined by the bond topology — harmonic bonds, harmonic angles, periodic torsions, improper torsions\n",
    "\n",
    "These are composed additively into a combined model for geometry optimization and molecular dynamics. The forces are summed; the energy ledger entries are assigned to their respective terms."
   ]
