    "## 3.2 Lennard-Jones 12-6 Potential\n",
    "\n",
    "The dominant nonbonded interaction in this framework is the Lennard-Jones potential. It captures two physical effects in a single analytic expression: short-range Pauli repulsion (the $r^{-12}$ term) and long-range London dispersion attraction (the $r^{-6}$ term).\n",
    "\n",
    "For atoms $i$ and $j$ separated by distance $r = |\\mathbf{r}_j - \\mathbf{r}_i|$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{LJ}(r) = 4\\varepsilon_{ij}\\left[\\left(\\frac{\\sigma_{ij}}{r}\\right)^{12} - \\left(\\frac{\\sigma_{ij}}{r}\\right)^{6}\\right]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The parameters have direct physical meaning:\n",
    "- $\\varepsilon_{ij}$ is the depth of the potential well, i.e., the interaction energy at the equilibrium separation. Typical values: 0.005 kcal/mol (Cu–Cu) to 0.505 kcal/mol (Al–Al).\n",
    "- $\\sigma_{ij}$ is the finite distance at which $U_\\text{LJ} = 0$ (the zero-crossing). Typical values: 2.76 Å (Zn) to 4.52 Å (Cs).\n",
    "- The equilibrium distance (potential minimum) is at $r_\\text{min} = 2^{1/6}\\sigma \\approx 1.122\\,\\sigma$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The radial force is the negative gradient:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "F_\\text{LJ}(r) = -\\frac{dU_\\text{LJ}}{dr} = \\frac{24\\varepsilon_{ij}}{r}\\left[2\\left(\\frac{\\sigma_{ij}}{r}\\right)^{12} - \\left(\\frac{\\sigma_{ij}}{r}\\right)^{6}\\right]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Positive $F_\\text{LJ}$ means repulsion (the atoms push apart). The force changes sign at $r = r_\\text{min}$: below this distance, the interaction is strongly repulsive; above it, weakly attractive.\n",
    "\n",
    "The vector force on atom $i$ from atom $j$ is $\\mathbf{f}_{ij} = F_\\text{LJ}(r) \\cdot \\hat{\\mathbf{r}}_{ij}$, where $\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}_{ij} = (\\mathbf{r}_i - \\mathbf{r}_j)/r$ is the unit vector from $j$ to $i$. Newton's third law is enforced explicitly: $\\mathbf{f}_{ji} = -\\mathbf{f}_{ij}$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The $r^{-12}$ exponent is a computational convenience, not a physical derivation. Pauli repulsion decays approximately exponentially, but $r^{-12} = (r^{-6})^2$ allows the repulsive term to be computed from the square of the attractive term, saving one exponentiation per pair. The $r^{-6}$ attractive term has firmer theoretical grounding: London's 1930 perturbation theory result for the interaction between two induced dipoles gives exactly $r^{-6}$ dependence at long range.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Reference:** Jones, J.E. (1924). \"On the determination of molecular fields.\" *Proc. R. Soc. A* 106(738), 463–477."
   ]
