    "## 3.3 Parameter Assignment and Combining Rules\n",
    "\n",
    "Each element has per-atom LJ parameters $(\\sigma_i, \\varepsilon_i)$ from the Universal Force Field (UFF) of Rappé et al. (1992). These parameters were fitted to reproduce crystal structures and heats of sublimation across the periodic table. The framework stores them for 20 elements explicitly, with the following values:\n",
    "\n",
    "| $Z$ | Element | $\\sigma$ (Å) | $\\varepsilon$ (kcal/mol) | Notes |\n",
    "|-----|---------|-------------|------------------------|-------|\n",
    "| 1 | H | 2.886 | 0.044 | |\n",
    "| 6 | C | 3.851 | 0.105 | Fallback for undefined elements |\n",
    "| 7 | N | 3.660 | 0.069 | |\n",
    "| 8 | O | 3.500 | 0.060 | |\n",
    "| 9 | F | 3.364 | 0.050 | |\n",
    "| 11 | Na | 3.328 | 0.030 | |\n",
    "| 12 | Mg | 3.021 | 0.111 | |\n",
    "| 13 | Al | 4.499 | 0.505 | |\n",
    "| 14 | Si | 4.295 | 0.402 | |\n",
    "| 15 | P | 4.147 | 0.305 | |\n",
    "| 16 | S | 4.035 | 0.274 | |\n",
    "| 17 | Cl | 3.947 | 0.227 | |\n",
    "| 18 | Ar | 3.400 | 0.238 | Noble gas, validated for LJ MD |\n",
    "| 20 | Ca | 3.399 | 0.238 | |\n",
    "| 26 | Fe | 2.912 | 0.013 | Very small $\\varepsilon$ — metallic bonding not captured by LJ |\n",
    "| 29 | Cu | 3.495 | 0.005 | Same caveat |\n",
    "| 30 | Zn | 2.763 | 0.124 | |\n",
    "| 54 | Xe | 4.404 | 0.332 | |\n",
    "| 55 | Cs | 4.517 | 0.045 | |\n",
    "| 84 | Po | 4.195 | 0.325 | |\n",
    "\n",
    "Cross-interaction parameters for a pair $(i, j)$ of different element types are computed via the Lorentz-Berthelot combining rules:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\sigma_{ij} = \\frac{\\sigma_i + \\sigma_j}{2} \\qquad \\text{(arithmetic mean — Lorentz, 1881)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\varepsilon_{ij} = \\sqrt{\\varepsilon_i \\cdot \\varepsilon_j} \\qquad \\text{(geometric mean — Berthelot, 1898)}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The arithmetic mean for $\\sigma$ has a physical basis: the contact distance between two spheres of radii $\\sigma_i/2$ and $\\sigma_j/2$ is $(\\sigma_i + \\sigma_j)/2$. The geometric mean for $\\varepsilon$ is more empirical — it assumes the dispersion interaction scales with the geometric mean of the polarizabilities, which is a reasonable approximation for similar atom types but breaks down for highly asymmetric pairs (e.g., Na–Ar).\n",
    "\n",
    "For elements without explicit UFF parameters, the framework uses carbon-like fallback values ($\\sigma = 3.851$ Å, $\\varepsilon = 0.105$ kcal/mol). This is flagged as an approximation in any output that involves such elements. The self-audit system classifies runs involving undefined-parameter elements as `OOD` (out of domain)."
