    "## 3.4 Coulomb Electrostatics\n",
    "\n",
    "For systems with nonzero partial charges, the electrostatic interaction between atoms $i$ and $j$ is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{Coul}(r) = \\frac{k_e \\, q_i \\, q_j}{r}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "F_\\text{Coul}(r) = \\frac{k_e \\, q_i \\, q_j}{r^2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $k_e = 332.0636$ kcal·Å·e$^{-2}$·mol$^{-1}$ is the Coulomb constant in AMBER-compatible units, and $q_i$ are partial atomic charges in units of the elementary charge $e$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Coulomb constant is derived from:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "k_e = \\frac{e^2 N_A}{4\\pi\\varepsilon_0} \\times \\frac{1}{4184 \\text{ J/kcal}} \\times 10^{10} \\text{ Å/m} = 332.0636 \\; \\frac{\\text{kcal}\\cdot\\text{Å}}{\\text{mol}\\cdot e^2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "### Known Limitation: Coulomb Force Coupling Instability\n",
    "\n",
    "The Coulomb energy term is computed correctly and reported in the energy ledger. However, **Coulomb forces are currently zeroed in the MD integrator loop**. The reason is a documented unit-conversion coupling instability between the Coulomb force magnitude and the velocity Verlet acceleration step.\n",
    "\n",
    "Specifically: the conversion from force (kcal/(mol·Å)) to acceleration (Å/fs²) via the factor $C_\\text{acc} = 1/C_\\text{KE} = 4.1841 \\times 10^{-4}$ produces correct temperatures for pure LJ systems (Ar gas at 162 K: measured $T \\approx 162$ K, 0.5% error) but causes ionic systems (NaCl) to diverge to $T \\sim 10^{32}$ K within a few hundred steps.\n",
    "\n",
    "The root cause has been isolated to the Coulomb-specific force magnitude scale. Coulomb forces between ions at 2.8 Å separation are $\\sim 100\\times$ larger than LJ forces, and the current acceleration conversion does not correctly handle the resulting velocity increments. This is an engineering problem — the physics and the formula are correct; the numerical pipeline has a gain error for the Coulomb channel.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Practical impact:** Formations driven by van der Waals interactions (noble gas clusters, hydrocarbons, molecular solids) are unaffected. Ionic formations (salts, metal oxides) are computed via single-point energy evaluation + FIRE minimization, which does not go through the velocity Verlet acceleration pathway."
   ]
