   "source": [
    "## 3.5 Cutoff Truncation and Switching\n",
    "\n",
    "All pairwise nonbonded interactions are truncated at a cutoff radius $r_c$ (default: 10.0 Å). Beyond this distance, $U(r) = 0$ and $F(r) = 0$. The justification is physical: LJ attraction decays as $r^{-6}$, so the contribution at $r = 3\\sigma$ is only $\\sim 0.3\\%$ of the well depth.\n",
    "\n",
    "A hard cutoff produces a discontinuity in the force at $r = r_c$, which creates an unphysical impulse every time an atom pair crosses the cutoff boundary. For dynamics, this is unacceptable — it violates energy conservation and produces heating artifacts.\n",
    "\n",
    "The framework applies a quintic switching function that smoothly turns off the interaction between $r_\\text{on} = 0.9\\,r_c$ and $r_c$. For $r \\in [r_\\text{on}, r_c]$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "S(x) = 1 - 10x^3 + 15x^4 - 6x^5, \\qquad x = \\frac{r - r_\\text{on}}{r_c - r_\\text{on}} \\in [0,1]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This polynomial satisfies:\n",
    "- $S(0) = 1$, $S(1) = 0$ (switches from full to zero)\n",
    "- $S'(0) = S'(1) = 0$ (force is continuous at both boundaries)\n",
    "- $S''(0) = S''(1) = 0$ (force derivative is continuous — needed for numerical integrator stability)\n",
    "\n",
    "The derivative used for force modification is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "S'(x) = \\frac{-30\\,x^2(1 - x)^2}{r_c - r_\\text{on}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The switched potential and force become:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U^\\text{sw}(r) = U(r) \\cdot S(x), \\qquad F_r^\\text{sw}(r) = F_r(r) \\cdot S(x) + U(r) \\cdot S'(x)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The second term arises from the chain rule: the force is the negative gradient of the switched potential, not the switch applied to the bare force. This distinction matters — applying the switch only to the force (ignoring the $U \\cdot S'$ term) would violate energy conservation.\n",
    "\n",
    "A minimum-distance guard of $r < 0.1$ Å skips the pair evaluation entirely, preventing the $r^{-12}$ singularity from producing overflow during initial configurations where atoms may accidentally overlap."
   ]
  },
