   "source": [
    "## 3.6 Periodic Boundary Conditions\n",
    "\n",
    "For bulk and crystalline systems, the simulation volume is replicated infinitely in all three Cartesian directions through orthogonal periodic boundary conditions (PBC).\n",
    "\n",
    "The simulation box has dimensions $(L_x, L_y, L_z)$. The fundamental operation is the **minimum image convention** (MIC): the displacement between atoms $i$ and $j$ is wrapped into the nearest periodic image:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\Delta r_\\alpha = r_{j,\\alpha} - r_{i,\\alpha} - L_\\alpha \\cdot \\text{round}\\!\\left(\\frac{r_{j,\\alpha} - r_{i,\\alpha}}{L_\\alpha}\\right), \\qquad \\alpha \\in \\{x, y, z\\}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This places $\\Delta r_\\alpha \\in (-L_\\alpha/2, \\, L_\\alpha/2]$. The distance $r = |\\Delta\\mathbf{r}|$ computed from the wrapped displacement is the distance to the nearest image of atom $j$.\n",
    "\n",
    "The MIC requires that the cutoff radius satisfies $r_c < L_\\alpha/2$ for all $\\alpha$. Otherwise, an atom could interact with a periodic image of itself, which is unphysical for pairwise potentials.\n",
    "\n",
    "Position wrapping into the primary cell $[0, L)$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "r_\\alpha \\leftarrow r_\\alpha - L_\\alpha \\cdot \\lfloor r_\\alpha / L_\\alpha \\rfloor\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "PBC is enabled only when all three box dimensions are positive. The box caches $1/L_\\alpha$ for performance (avoiding repeated divisions in the inner loop). For isolated molecules in vacuum, PBC is disabled and bare Euclidean displacement is used.\n",
    "\n",
    "The current implementation supports only orthogonal boxes (90° angles). Triclinic boxes for non-cubic crystals are a future extension."
   ]
