    "## 3.7 VSEPR Mode vs. MD Mode\n",
    "\n",
    "The framework maintains two distinct nonbonded interaction regimes, reflecting two fundamentally different use cases.\n",
    "\n",
    "**VSEPR mode** uses the Weeks-Chandler-Andersen (WCA) potential — the purely repulsive portion of LJ, shifted so that $U_\\text{WCA}(r_\\text{min}) = 0$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{WCA}(r) = \\begin{cases}\n",
    "4\\varepsilon\\left[(\\sigma/r)^{12} - (\\sigma/r)^6\\right] + \\varepsilon & r < 2^{1/6}\\sigma \\\\\n",
    "0 & r \\geq 2^{1/6}\\sigma\n",
    "\\end{cases}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with very small $\\varepsilon$ (0.001–0.01 kcal/mol). The purpose is purely geometric: prevent atom overlap during VSEPR geometry prediction without introducing attractive interactions that would compete with the bonded terms. In this mode, the molecular shape is determined entirely by bond lengths, bond angles, and steric repulsion — which is exactly the VSEPR model.\n",
    "\n",
    "**MD mode** uses the full LJ 12-6 potential with UFF-calibrated parameters, plus (when functional) Coulomb interactions. The purpose is thermodynamic: sample the canonical ensemble at a specified temperature and produce physically meaningful formation energies.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Property | VSEPR Mode | MD Mode |\n",
    "|----------|-----------|--------|\n",
    "| Potential | WCA (repulsion only) | Full LJ 12-6 |\n",
    "| $\\varepsilon$ | 0.001–0.01 kcal/mol | UFF values (0.005–0.505 kcal/mol) |\n",
    "| Coulomb | Disabled | Computed (force contribution pending) |\n",
    "| Purpose | Geometry optimization | Thermodynamic formation |\n",
    "| 1-3 pair scaling | 0.0–0.3 | Per force field specification |\n",
    "\n",
    "The two modes share the same State, the same IModel interface, and the same integrators. They differ only in which model instance is plugged in and what parameters it carries."
