    "## 4.2 Temperature from Kinetic Energy\n",
    "\n",
    "Temperature in molecular simulation is not a thermostat dial. It is a statistical-mechanical observable computed from the microscopic state via the equipartition theorem.\n",
    "\n",
    "For a system of $N$ classical particles, the equipartition theorem states that each quadratic degree of freedom contributes $\\frac{1}{2} k_B T$ to the average kinetic energy:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\langle K \\rangle = \\frac{N_\\text{df}}{2} k_B T\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $N_\\text{df} = 3N - N_\\text{constraints}$ is the number of translational degrees of freedom. The instantaneous temperature is therefore:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "T(t) = \\frac{2 K(t)}{N_\\text{df} \\, k_B}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $K = \\sum_{i=1}^{N} \\frac{1}{2} m_i |\\mathbf{v}_i|^2$.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a fluctuating quantity. In a finite system, instantaneous temperature varies from step to step — the fluctuations scale as $\\sqrt{2 / N_\\text{df}}$ relative to the mean. A 100-atom system at 300 K will show $T$ fluctuating roughly between 250 K and 350 K. This is not a defect; it is the correct canonical distribution. The *thermodynamic* temperature is $\\langle T \\rangle$ averaged over equilibrated configurations.\n",
    "\n",
    "For systems with $N_\\text{constraints} = 0$ (no rigid bonds, no frozen atoms), $N_\\text{df} = 3N$. If center-of-mass motion has been removed, $N_\\text{df} = 3N - 3$."
   ]
