    "## 5.1 Velocity Verlet (NVE Ensemble)\n",
    "\n",
    "The default integrator for conservative dynamics is the velocity Verlet algorithm. It is the standard choice in molecular simulation for good reason: it is symplectic (preserves phase space volume), time-reversible (satisfies microscopic reversibility), and second-order accurate in positions and velocities.\n",
    "\n",
    "The algorithm advances positions and velocities from time $t$ to $t + \\Delta t$ in four steps:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_i\\!\\left(t + \\tfrac{\\Delta t}{2}\\right) = \\mathbf{v}_i(t) + \\frac{\\Delta t}{2 m_i} \\mathbf{F}_i(t)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{x}_i(t + \\Delta t) = \\mathbf{x}_i(t) + \\Delta t \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_i\\!\\left(t + \\tfrac{\\Delta t}{2}\\right)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{F}_i(t + \\Delta t) = -\\nabla_{\\mathbf{x}_i} U\\bigl(\\mathbf{X}(t + \\Delta t)\\bigr)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_i(t + \\Delta t) = \\mathbf{v}_i\\!\\left(t + \\tfrac{\\Delta t}{2}\\right) + \\frac{\\Delta t}{2 m_i} \\mathbf{F}_i(t + \\Delta t)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The symplectic property means that the total energy $E = K + U$ is conserved not exactly but to a bounded error that does not grow with time. For a well-parameterized LJ system at $\\Delta t = 1$ fs, the energy drift is typically $O(10^{-4})$ kcal/mol per particle over $10^4$ steps.\n",
    "\n",
    "The force evaluation (step 3) is the expensive part — it dominates the cost of the simulation. Each of the other steps is $O(N)$; the force evaluation is $O(N^2)$ for the current all-pairs implementation (no cell lists or neighbor lists yet).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Default parameters:** $\\Delta t = 1.0$ fs, 10,000 steps, trajectory saved every 100 steps."
   ]
