    "## 5.2 Langevin Dynamics (NVT Ensemble)\n",
    "\n",
    "For canonical (constant-temperature) sampling, the framework uses Langevin dynamics. The idea is to couple each particle to a fictitious heat bath via a friction term and a random force:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "m_i \\frac{d\\mathbf{v}_i}{dt} = \\mathbf{F}_i(\\mathbf{x}) - \\gamma m_i \\mathbf{v}_i + \\sqrt{2\\gamma m_i k_B T} \\; \\boldsymbol{\\xi}_i(t)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The three terms have distinct physical roles:\n",
    "- $\\mathbf{F}_i(\\mathbf{x})$: deterministic conservative force from the potential\n",
    "- $-\\gamma m_i \\mathbf{v}_i$: friction that removes kinetic energy (dissipation)\n",
    "- $\\sqrt{2\\gamma m_i k_B T} \\; \\boldsymbol{\\xi}_i(t)$: random Gaussian kicks that inject kinetic energy (fluctuation)\n",
    "\n",
    "The fluctuation-dissipation theorem guarantees that these two terms balance at equilibrium: the friction removes energy at exactly the rate the random force adds it, and the resulting velocity distribution is Maxwell-Boltzmann at temperature $T$.\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\gamma$ is the friction coefficient with units of inverse time (default: 0.1 fs$^{-1}$). Large $\\gamma$ means strong coupling to the bath (fast equilibration, overdamped dynamics). Small $\\gamma$ means weak coupling (slow equilibration, nearly Newtonian dynamics). The dynamics are not Hamiltonian — energy is exchanged with the bath — so total energy fluctuates.\n",
    "\n",
    "The current discretization is Euler-Maruyama (first-order stochastic integrator):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{v}_i(t+\\Delta t) = \\mathbf{v}_i(t) + \\left[\\frac{\\mathbf{F}_i}{m_i} - \\gamma\\mathbf{v}_i\\right]\\Delta t + \\sqrt{\\frac{2\\gamma k_B T}{m_i}}\\,\\sqrt{\\Delta t}\\;\\mathbf{R}_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\mathbf{R}_i \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0,1)$ is a 3-component standard normal random vector. Higher-order integrators (BAOAB, G-JF) are noted as future extensions.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Berendsen Velocity Rescaling\n",
    "\n",
    "An alternative weak-coupling thermostat is available for the NVT mode in `meso-sim`. Every 10 velocity Verlet steps, velocities are rescaled:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\lambda = \\sqrt{1 + \\frac{\\Delta t}{\\tau}\\left(\\frac{T_\\text{target}}{T_\\text{current}} - 1\\right)}, \\qquad \\mathbf{v}_i \\leftarrow \\lambda \\cdot \\mathbf{v}_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with coupling time $\\tau = 100$ fs. The Berendsen thermostat drives $T \\to T_\\text{target}$ exponentially. It does *not* generate the correct canonical fluctuations (the kinetic energy distribution is too narrow), so it should be used only for equilibration, not for computing fluctuation-dependent properties (heat capacity, free energy)."
   ]
