    "---\n",
    "# §6 — Formation Physics and Emergent Structure\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6.1 Bonded Interaction Terms\n",
    "\n",
    "The bonded force field computes intramolecular forces from the bond topology stored in the State's edge list $\\mathbf{B}$. Four distinct terms are implemented, each capturing a different scale of internal molecular deformation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Harmonic Bond Stretching\n",
    "\n",
    "The simplest intramolecular term: a harmonic spring between bonded atoms.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{bond} = k_b (r - r_0)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $r$ is the current distance and $r_0$ is the equilibrium bond length.\n",
    "\n",
    "The force is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{F}_i = -2k_b(r - r_0)\\,\\hat{\\mathbf{r}}_{ij}, \\qquad \\mathbf{F}_j = -\\mathbf{F}_i\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is Hooke's law applied to covalent bonds. It is exact near equilibrium (the Taylor expansion of any smooth potential about its minimum starts with a quadratic term) and progressively worse for large displacements. A Morse potential would be more physical for bond dissociation, but harmonic potentials are adequate for formation detection where bonds do not break.\n",
    "\n",
    "Default generic parameters: $k_b = 310$ kcal/(mol·Å²), $r_0 = 1.54$ Å (C–C single bond equivalent).\n",
    "\n",
    "### Harmonic Angle Bending\n",
    "\n",
    "For three atoms $i$–$j$–$k$ where $j$ is the vertex:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{angle} = k_\\theta(\\theta - \\theta_0)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\theta = \\arccos\\!\\left(\\frac{\\mathbf{r}_{ij} \\cdot \\mathbf{r}_{kj}}{|\\mathbf{r}_{ij}| \\, |\\mathbf{r}_{kj}|}\\right)$ is the angle between vectors from the vertex to the two neighbors.\n",
    "\n",
    "The force derivation is nontrivial because $\\theta$ depends on three positions. The chain rule gives:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\mathbf{F}_i = \\frac{-2k_\\theta(\\theta - \\theta_0)}{\\sin\\theta}\\left[\\frac{\\mathbf{r}_{kj}}{|\\mathbf{r}_{ij}||\\mathbf{r}_{kj}|} - \\frac{\\mathbf{r}_{ij}\\cos\\theta}{|\\mathbf{r}_{ij}|^2}\\right]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "with $\\mathbf{F}_k$ by symmetry (swap $i \\leftrightarrow k$) and $\\mathbf{F}_j = -(\\mathbf{F}_i + \\mathbf{F}_k)$ by momentum conservation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Default: $k_\\theta = 60$ kcal/(mol·rad²), $\\theta_0 = 109.5° = 1.91$ rad (tetrahedral).\n",
    "\n",
    "### Periodic Torsion (Dihedral)\n",
    "\n",
    "For four atoms $i$–$j$–$k$–$l$ where $j$–$k$ is the central bond (rotation axis):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{tors} = V_n\\bigl[1 + \\cos(n\\phi - \\gamma)\\bigr]\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\phi$ is the dihedral angle, $n$ is the periodicity ($n = 3$ for sp³-sp³ bonds like ethane), $V_n$ is the barrier height, and $\\gamma$ is the phase offset.\n",
    "\n",
    "The dihedral angle is computed from the two plane normals $\\mathbf{n}_1 = \\mathbf{b}_1 \\times \\mathbf{b}_2$ and $\\mathbf{n}_2 = \\mathbf{b}_2 \\times \\mathbf{b}_3$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\phi = \\text{atan2}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\mathbf{b}_2 \\cdot (\\mathbf{n}_1 \\times \\mathbf{n}_2)}{|\\mathbf{b}_2|}, \\; \\mathbf{n}_1 \\cdot \\mathbf{n}_2\\right)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Force distribution onto the four atoms uses the Blondel-Karplus (1996) formulation, which avoids the singularity that arises when the dihedral angle approaches $0$ or $\\pi$ (planar configurations). The key expressions are:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial\\phi}{\\partial\\mathbf{r}_i} = -\\frac{|\\mathbf{b}_2|}{|\\mathbf{n}_1|^2}\\,\\mathbf{n}_1, \\qquad \\frac{\\partial\\phi}{\\partial\\mathbf{r}_l} = +\\frac{|\\mathbf{b}_2|}{|\\mathbf{n}_2|^2}\\,\\mathbf{n}_2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The forces on the two central atoms ($j$ and $k$) involve both plane normals and the bond angles at those vertices. The full expressions contain six coefficients derived from the bond lengths and angles, all implemented following the Blondel-Karplus paper equation by equation.\n",
    "\n",
    "Default: $n = 3$, $V_n = 1.5$ kcal/mol, $\\gamma = 0$.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Improper Torsion\n",
    "\n",
    "Maintains planarity for sp² centers:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{imp} = k_\\text{imp}(\\psi - \\psi_0)^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\psi$ is the out-of-plane angle, computed using the same dihedral machinery (reinterpretation of the atom ordering), and wrapped to $[-\\pi, \\pi]$. Default: $k_\\text{imp} = 10$–$50$ kcal/(mol·rad²), $\\psi_0 = 0$.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Topology Generation\n",
    "\n",
    "The bonded topology is inferred automatically from the bond graph:\n",
    "- **Angles**: all triplets $(i, j, k)$ where $j$ is bonded to both $i$ and $k$\n",
    "- **Dihedrals**: all quartets $(i, j, k, l)$ along connected bond chains\n",
    "- **Impropers**: currently require explicit specification for sp² centers\n",
    "\n",
    "This auto-generation means the engine can process any molecular topology without a pre-built parameter file. The trade-off is that all generated angles get the same force constant and equilibrium angle (tetrahedral), and all dihedrals get the same barrier. Element-type-specific parameterization — using covalent radii to set $r_0$, electronegativity differences to set $k_b$ — is the natural next step but not yet implemented."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6.2 Formation as Emergence\n",
    "\n",
    "With the interaction model fully defined — nonbonded (§3) and bonded (§6.1) — we can now state what \"formation\" means in this framework.\n",
    "\n",
    "A formation is a **local minimum of the potential energy surface** reached by a physically motivated search procedure. It is not a guess, not a database lookup, not a hand-drawn structure. It is the answer to the question: if you put these atoms in a box and let physics run, what geometry does the system relax into?\n",
    "\n",
    "The search procedure is:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Place $N$ atoms in a simulation volume with initial positions (random, lattice, or VSEPR-predicted)\n",
    "2. Initialize velocities at temperature $T$ from the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution\n",
    "3. Propagate under Newtonian or Langevin dynamics for $n_\\text{steps}$ steps\n",
    "4. Extract snapshots at intervals\n",
    "5. Quench each snapshot with FIRE minimization\n",
    "6. The quenched structure is a formation\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 3 provides thermal exploration — the system crosses energy barriers and samples different regions of configuration space. Step 5 provides structural identification — FIRE projects the thermal fluctuations away and reveals the underlying equilibrium geometry.\n",
    "\n",
    "Multiple formations may emerge from the same composition at the same temperature, depending on the random seed (which determines initial velocities and therefore the dynamical trajectory). This is not a failure of the method; it reflects the physical reality that most molecular systems have multiple local minima. Ethane has a staggered and an eclipsed conformer. Butane has trans, gauche+, and gauche− conformers. Protein folding involves thousands of metastable states.\n",
    "\n",
    "The engine treats all converged local minima as valid formations. Ranking is done by the scoring function (§7), not by discarding metastable states."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6.3 Basin Mapping and Conformer Ensembles\n",
    "\n",
    "A **basin of attraction** is the set of all initial configurations from which FIRE minimization converges to the same local minimum. Different basins lead to different formations; the relative basin volumes determine the statistical weights of different structures.\n",
    "\n",
    "The adaptive sampling mode maps the basin landscape:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Start from a reference structure\n",
    "2. Perturb all positions by Gaussian noise ($\\sigma = 0.2$ Å)\n",
    "3. FIRE-minimize the perturbed structure\n",
    "4. Record the final energy\n",
    "5. Repeat $n_\\text{samples}$ times\n",
    "6. Monitor energy convergence via the stationarity gate\n",
    "\n",
    "If all samples converge to the same energy (within tolerance), the landscape is \"funnel-like\" — there is essentially one dominant basin and the formation is robust. If multiple distinct energies emerge, there are competing basins, and the formation depends on initial conditions.\n",
    "\n",
    "For flexible molecules, the conformer ensemble is generated similarly but with larger perturbations ($\\sigma = 0.3$ Å) to sample different rotameric states. Conformers are clustered by RMSD after Kabsch alignment (§7.3): structures with RMSD below a threshold (default: 0.5 Å) are considered the same conformer.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Boltzmann population of conformer $i$ at temperature $T$ is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "p_i = \\frac{e^{-E_i / k_B T}}{\\sum_j e^{-E_j / k_B T}}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This connects the static formation results back to thermodynamics: the probability of observing each conformer at equilibrium."
   ]
