    "---\n",
    "# §7 — Statistical Interpretation Layer\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7.1 Welford's Algorithm for Online Statistics\n",
    "\n",
    "Throughout the framework, running mean and variance are computed via Welford's one-pass algorithm (1962). This is not a performance choice — it is a numerical necessity.\n",
    "\n",
    "The naive formula $\\text{Var}(x) = \\overline{x^2} - \\bar{x}^2$ is catastrophically unstable when $\\overline{x^2}$ and $\\bar{x}^2$ are both large and nearly equal, which is exactly what happens for energy trajectories (energies of −500.001, −500.002, −499.998, ...). The subtraction produces garbage.\n",
    "\n",
    "Welford's update, given sample $x_n$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\bar{x}_n = \\bar{x}_{n-1} + \\frac{x_n - \\bar{x}_{n-1}}{n}\n",
    "$$  
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "M_{2,n} = M_{2,n-1} + (x_n - \\bar{x}_{n-1})(x_n - \\bar{x}_n)\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{Var}(x) = \\frac{M_2}{n-1}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The key property: no running sum of $x^2$ is ever formed. The variance is accumulated through products of *deviations from the running mean*, which are small even when the values themselves are large.\n",
    "\n",
    "The framework extends this to 3D vectors via `OnlineVec3Stats`, which tracks per-component means and variances for positions and velocities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7.2 Convergence Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "The stationarity gate determines when an observable has reached statistical equilibrium. The test is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "|x_\\text{new} - \\bar{x}| < 3\\sigma + \\epsilon_\\text{mean}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "That is: a new sample is \"consistent\" if it falls within three standard deviations of the running mean, plus a small tolerance for near-zero variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "Convergence requires $k$ **consecutive** passes (default $k = 10$). A single outlier resets the counter. This is conservative by design — it is better to run 100 extra samples than to declare convergence prematurely and report an unstable formation as stable.\n",
    "\n",
    "The `ObservableTracker` monitors total energy, bond energy, vdW energy, and Coulomb energy simultaneously, using independent `OnlineStats` instances for each."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7.3 Structural Comparison: Kabsch Alignment\n",
    "\n",
    "Comparing two molecular structures requires accounting for overall translation and rotation. Two identical molecules at different positions and orientations have RMSD $\\neq 0$ in raw Cartesian space but RMSD $= 0$ after optimal superposition.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Kabsch algorithm finds the optimal rigid-body rotation:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Center both structures at their centers of mass\n",
    "2. Compute the cross-covariance matrix: $\\mathbf{H} = \\sum_i \\mathbf{r}_i^\\text{target} \\otimes \\mathbf{r}_i^\\text{ref}$\n",
    "3. Singular value decomposition: $\\mathbf{H} = \\mathbf{U}\\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}\\mathbf{V}^T$\n",
    "4. Optimal rotation: $\\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{V}\\mathbf{U}^T$\n",
    "5. Chirality correction: if $\\det(\\mathbf{R}) < 0$, negate the column of $\\mathbf{V}$ corresponding to the smallest singular value\n",
    "\n",
    "The RMSD after alignment is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{RMSD} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{N}\\sum_i |\\mathbf{R}\\,\\mathbf{r}_i^\\text{target} - \\mathbf{r}_i^\\text{ref}|^2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the metric used for conformer clustering, regression detection (has a formation changed?), and trajectory analysis (how much does the structure fluctuate?)."
   ]
