    "---\n",
    "# §8 — Collision-Driven Reaction and Topology Evolution\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8.1 The Reaction Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "Within a single simulation run, the bond graph is static — bonds do not form or break. This is the standard approximation of classical molecular mechanics: the topology is fixed, and the force field computes deformations around that topology.\n",
    "\n",
    "Reactions — changes to the bond graph — happen *between* runs, mediated by the reaction engine. The engine proposes reactions by analyzing the electronic properties of two molecules, matching reactive sites using the HSAB (Hard-Soft Acid-Base) principle, and estimating the thermodynamic feasibility of the proposed transformation.\n",
    "\n",
    "A proposed reaction has the form:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "A + B \\;\\xrightarrow{\\text{template}}\\; C + D\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where the template specifies the mechanism (substitution, addition, elimination, rearrangement, redox, pericyclic, radical, acid-base) and the geometric, electronic, and thermodynamic constraints.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8.2 Reactive Site Identification\n",
    "\n",
    "Reactive sites are identified via Fukui functions, which are finite-difference approximations to the electron density response:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $f_i^+$: susceptibility to nucleophilic attack (electron donation)\n",
    "- $f_i^-$: susceptibility to electrophilic attack (electron withdrawal)\n",
    "- $f_i^0$: susceptibility to radical attack\n",
    "\n",
    "The HSAB principle matches soft nucleophiles with soft electrophiles and hard nucleophiles with hard electrophiles. Chemical hardness is computed from the periodic table:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\eta = \\frac{\\text{IE}_1 - \\text{EA}}{2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Reaction templates impose constraints: minimum Fukui indices for the attacking and attacked sites, maximum hardness mismatch for HSAB compliance, geometric constraints (approach angle, distance), and thermodynamic filters (maximum barrier, minimum exothermicity).\n",
    "\n",
    "## 8.3 Barrier Estimation\n",
    "\n",
    "Activation barriers are estimated via the Bell-Evans-Polanyi principle:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "E_a = E_a^0 + \\alpha \\cdot \\Delta H\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $E_a^0$ is an intrinsic barrier (default: 10 kcal/mol), $\\alpha$ is a transfer coefficient, and $\\Delta H$ is the reaction enthalpy estimated from formation energies. This is a linear free-energy relationship — it works for families of related reactions (same mechanism, different substituents) and fails for mechanistically different reactions.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is clearly an effective approximation. The framework labels all barrier estimates as such and never presents them as computed transition-state energies."
   ]
  },
