    "---\n",
    "# §9 — Electronic Property Prediction\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9.1 Scope of Electronic Predictions\n",
    "\n",
    "The formation engine is a classical-mechanical framework. It does not solve the Schrödinger equation. However, molecular properties that depend on electron distribution — partial charges, dipole moments, ionization potentials — can be estimated from topology and periodic-table data using well-established empirical models.\n",
    "\n",
    "All electronic predictions produced by this framework are **labeled effective approximations** derived from elemental properties. They are suitable for screening and ranking (\"is molecule A likely more polar than molecule B?\") but not for quantitative predictions that require quantum-mechanical accuracy.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Electronegativity Equilibration\n",
    "\n",
    "Partial charges are estimated from the electronegativity equalization method (QEq). From the periodic table:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Mulliken electronegativity: $\\chi = (\\text{IE}_1 + \\text{EA})/2$\n",
    "- Chemical hardness: $\\eta = (\\text{IE}_1 - \\text{EA})/2$\n",
    "- Electrophilicity index: $\\omega = \\chi^2 / (2\\eta)$\n",
    "\n",
    "These are per-atom estimates. Molecular-level charge distribution requires solving the electronegativity equalization equations, which is reserved for future implementation.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Reactivity Indices\n",
    "\n",
    "From partial charges at $N$, $N+1$, and $N-1$ electrons:\n",
    "\n",
    "- $f^+ = q(N) - q(N-1)$: nucleophilic attack susceptibility\n",
    "- $f^- = q(N+1) - q(N)$: electrophilic attack susceptibility\n",
    "- $f^0 = (f^+ + f^-)/2$: radical attack susceptibility\n",
    "\n",
    "These Fukui functions are diagnostic tools for the reaction engine (§8), not dynamic variables that feed back into the equations of motion."
   ]
  },
