    "## 13.1 Quantum-Informed Corrections\n",
    "\n",
    "The classical force field provides the majority of the potential energy landscape. Quantum-informed corrections can be layered additively:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "U_\\text{corrected}(\\mathbf{X}) = U_\\text{classical}(\\mathbf{X}) + \\Delta U_\\text{QM}(\\mathbf{X})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $\\Delta U_\\text{QM}$ is trained on $(U_\\text{DFT} - U_\\text{classical})$ from reference calculations. This delta-learning approach leverages the classical potential for the bulk of the energy landscape and uses the correction to capture exchange-correlation, charge transfer, and dispersion effects that classical models miss.\n",
    "\n",
    "The critical requirement: the classical model must remain independently evaluable. The correction is an optional layer, not a replacement.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 13.2 Reactive Dynamics\n",
    "\n",
    "The current bond graph is static during simulation. Reactive extensions require:\n",
    "- Bond order potentials (e.g., ReaxFF) where bond order is a continuous function of distance and environment\n",
    "- Graph mutation rules: when a bond forms or breaks, $\\mathbf{B}$ is updated, triggering re-inference of angles and dihedrals\n",
    "- Energy conservation across topology changes\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the path to true in-situ formation dynamics — watching structures assemble rather than quenching pre-placed atoms.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 13.3 States of Matter\n",
    "\n",
    "The engine currently handles molecular and crystalline formations. Extensions:\n",
    "- **Liquid**: NPT barostat + long equilibration\n",
    "- **Amorphous solid**: melt-quench protocol (heat above melting point, cool rapidly)\n",
    "- **Plasma**: high-temperature ionization model + charge dynamics\n",
    "\n",
    "Each state of matter uses the same State → IModel → Formation pipeline with different models, ensembles, and analysis tools.\n",
    "\n",
    "## 13.4 Scale\n",
    "\n",
    "| Scale | Atoms | Method | Formation type |\n",
    "|-------|-------|--------|----------------|\n",
    "| Molecular | 2–50 | Full MM + FIRE | Molecules, dimers |\n",
    "| Cluster | 50–500 | MD + quench | Nanoparticles, aggregates |\n",
    "| Bulk | 500–10,000 | PBC + supercell | Crystals, amorphous solids |\n",
    "| Mesoscale | 10,000+ | CG + PMF | Polymers, membranes |"
